-- Towers of Hanoi — durability proof, not computation.
-- Pre-computed moves. Agent just closes steps. Proves crash-recovery at scale.
-- 3 disks = 7 moves (2^n - 1).

## towers-of-hanoi

  input param.source_peg : str default("A")
  input param.target_peg : str default("C")
  input param.auxiliary_peg : str default("B")

  -- Each step is a trivial acknowledgment cell.
  -- The agent reads the instruction and closes the bead.
  -- This is not LLM work — it's deterministic execution.

  # setup : text
    user>
      Verify initial state: all 3 disks stacked on peg {{param.source_peg}}.
      Largest on bottom.
    accept>
      Initial state verified.
  #/

  # move-1 : text
    - setup
    user>
      Move disk 1: {{param.source_peg}} → {{param.target_peg}}
  #/

  # move-2 : text
    - move-1
    user>
      Move disk 2: {{param.source_peg}} → {{param.auxiliary_peg}}
  #/

  # move-3 : text
    - move-2
    user>
      Move disk 1: {{param.target_peg}} → {{param.auxiliary_peg}}
  #/

  # move-4 : text
    - move-3
    user>
      Move disk 3: {{param.source_peg}} → {{param.target_peg}}
  #/

  # move-5 : text
    - move-4
    user>
      Move disk 1: {{param.auxiliary_peg}} → {{param.source_peg}}
  #/

  # move-6 : text
    - move-5
    user>
      Move disk 2: {{param.auxiliary_peg}} → {{param.target_peg}}
  #/

  # move-7 : text
    - move-6
    user>
      Move disk 1: {{param.source_peg}} → {{param.target_peg}}
  #/

  # verify : llm
    - move-7
    user>
      Verify final state: all 3 disks on peg {{param.target_peg}}.
      Tower intact. All moves were legal.
    format> verification
      { valid: "true" | "false", disk_count: number, final_peg: str }

    ```oracle
    json_parse(output);
    assert output.valid == "true";
    assert output.disk_count == 3;
    ```
  #/

##/
